Glamorgan fines were very rare, and the few that remained were passed in the lord's court at Cardiff. In England, fines were passed in the King's com-ts. before the justices of the Common Pleas3 but, as the late Mr. Burtt observed, Llanblethian being a Welsh manor, and belonging to the lord of Glamorgan (a lord Mareher), the fine is passed in the lord's local court, and before his representative, the sheriff. Sir Walter Skull, who held that office, belonged to a Breconshire family, and his connexion with Glamorgan is unknown. Thomas Butler was. no doubt. of Dunraven. The fine of two shillings in lieu of a ‘⁶ sore ’' sparrow-hawk is in recognition of the right of the lord. Howell and Alioia or Aliva Vaughan occur also in a following Chai-ter of 1463. John Bassett, also there named, was of Beaupre.
